{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Transformer architectures have led to remarkable progress in automated repair applications.",
    "However, despite their successes, modern transformers rely on the self-attention mechanism, whose time-and space-complexity is quadratic in the length of the input that requires substantial computing resources when encountering long sequences.",
    "Recently, many alternative architectures have been proposed to mitigate the long sequence challenge and computing burden of transformers.",
    "For example, Beltagy et al. [13] presented Longformer which uses global and local attention windows to mitigate the memory and time bottleneck of the self-attention mechanism from O(ns×ns) to O(ns×w), with ns being the sequence length and w being the average window size.",
    "In particular, the base-size Longformer can process up to 4,096 subword tokens."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "For example, Beltagy et al. [13] presented Longformer which uses global and local attention windows to mitigate the memory and time bottleneck of the self-attention mechanism from O(ns×ns) to O(ns×w), with ns being the sequence length and w being the average window size."
  ]
}